6:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC uses standard 8-hour funding intervals with rates typically ranging from -0.375% to +0.375% daily. RabbitX implements hourly funding settlements, allowing for more granular rate capture but with smaller individual payments. MEXC's zero maker fees provide significant cost advantages for arbitrageurs, while RabbitX's frequent settlements can compound returns more effectively during sustained rate periods. Both platforms calculate rates using similar mark-to-index methodologies, though RabbitX's DEX structure may show more volatile rates due to lower liquidity."}]]}]
7:["$","$Lc",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which exchange offers better funding rate opportunities?","answer":"MEXC typically offers more diverse opportunities due to its extensive altcoin listings and zero maker fees. RabbitX provides faster rate capture through hourly settlements but is limited to major pairs with lower liquidity."},{"question":"How do the funding calculation methods differ between platforms?","answer":"Both use standard perpetual funding formulas based on mark-to-index price differences. MEXC applies rates every 8 hours with typical bounds, while RabbitX calculates hourly with potentially higher volatility due to DEX mechanics."},{"question":"What are the main execution risks on each platform?","answer":"MEXC faces counterparty risk and potential volume manipulation concerns. RabbitX carries smart contract risk and liquidity constraints that may prevent large position entries or exits during volatile periods."},{"question":"Which platform is better for automated arbitrage strategies?","answer":"MEXC's API stability and zero maker fees favor automated strategies, though order book depth should be monitored. RabbitX's hourly settlements appeal to bots but require careful liquidity assessment before execution."}]}]
